@NODE Introduction "Introduction to GSM"

@{u}Introduction to GSM@{uu}

The Graphic System Monitor (GSM) is a system monitoring tool that shows
graphically:
 o Memory usage (both CHIP and FAST)
 o Memory fragmentation
 o CPU idle rate

I built GSM because I felt that there was no tool available that had all 
of these options. There are many free memory gauges, but these are just
like fuel gauges, and don't produce the nice "hartbeat" like graph I
wanted. Some tools do make such a graph, but they don't show all options 
at the same time.
Some tools measure CPU load or idle rate, but many do so in a terrible
inaccurate way (counting the number of READY tasks).
Very few tools show memory fragmentation, and those who do, present the
information in textual form, not graphically.

That's why I decided to build my own tool that shows everything I want
to see the way I want it to see.

GSM was inspired on the very old PerfMon tool by Dale Luck, but it has some
extra options. Besides, the PerfMon tool was developed for WB 1.x, and 
looks ugly on a 2.x/3.x Workbench screen.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Requirements "System Requirements"

@{u}System Requirements@{uu}

To successfully use GSM, you need:

 o An Amiga with Kickstart/Workbench 2.0 or later
 o A CPU and some memory ;-)

@ENDNODE
@NODE Installation "Installing GSM"

@{u}Installing GSM@{uu}

Well, there is not much to say about this.

Just copy the executable and this guide (and the icons) to where you want
them to be.
That's it.

GSM doesn't need third-party libraries, and doesn't need any Assigns.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Quick Start Links: @{" Use from Workbench " link WBStart}
                    @{" Use from Shell     " link ShellStart}

@ENDNODE
@NODE WBStart "Use GSM from Workbench"

@{u}Use GSM from Workbench@{uu}

GSM can be started from the Workbench like any other program: just double-
click on its icon.

You can set several @{" Tool Types " link Tooltypes} using the Workbench information
menu choice.

Alternatively, GSM can be started from the @{" Shell " link ShellStart}.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Quick Start Link: @{" Features " link Features}

@ENDNODE
@NODE ShellStart "Use GSM from the Shell"

@{u}Use GSM from the Shell@{uu}

GSM can be started from the Shell (or CLI).

Format:     GSM  [CHIP] [FAST] [CPU] [FRAG] [NOFRAG] [GRID] [NOGRID]
                 [DELAY @{i}delay@{ui}] [WINDOW @{i}window_spec@{ui}]
                 [PUBSCREEN @{i}screen_name@{ui}]
                 [FONT @{i}font_name@{ui}] [FONTH @{i}font_height@{ui}]
                 [BGPEN @{i}pen@{ui}] [FG1PEN @{i}pen@{ui}] [FG2PEN @{i}pen@{ui}]
                 [GRIDPEN @{i}pen@{ui}] [TITLEBAR @{i}yes_or_no@{ui}]

Template:   GSM  CHIP/S,FAST/S,CPU/S,FRAG/S,NOFRAG/S,GRID/S,NOGRID/S,
                 DELAY/N/K,WINDOW/K,PUBSCREEN/K,FONT/K,FONTH/N/K,
                 BGPEN/N/K,FG1PEN/N/K,FG2PEN/N/K,GRIDPEN/N/K,TITLEBAR/K

When started from the shell, GSM tries to read its Workbench icon file. It
then uses the @{" Tool Types " link Tooltypes} in that file for its default configuration.
The command line arguments can be used to override the Tool Type settings.

GSM supports the following command line arguments:

   @{b}CHIP@{ub}
   @{b}FAST@{ub}
   @{b}CPU@{ub}
            If @{i}any@{ui} of these three are present, they override @{i}all three@{ui}
            of the corresponding @{" Tool Types " link Tooltypes}.

   @{b}NOFRAG@{ub}
   @{b}NOGRID@{ub}
   @{b}DELAY @{i}number_of_milliseconds@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}WINDOW @{i}left@{ui}/@{i}top@{ui}/@{i}width@{ui}/@{i}height@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}PUBSCREEN @{i}Public_Screen_Name@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}FONT=@{i}fontname.font@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}FONTH=@{i}font_height@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}BGPEN=@{i}pen_number@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}FG1PEN=@{i}pen_number@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}FG2PEN=@{i}pen_number@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}GRIDPEN=@{i}pen_number@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}TITLEBAR=@{i}yes_or_no@{ui}@{ub}
            The meaning of these arguments are the same as the
            corresponding @{" Tool Types " link Tooltypes}

   @{b}FRAG@{ub}
            Can be used to override a NOFRAG Tool Type setting.

   @{b}GRID@{ub}
            Can be used to override a NOGRID Tool Type setting.

Alternatively, GSM can be started from the @{" Workbench " link WBStart}.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Quick Start Link: @{" Features " link Features}
 
@ENDNODE
@NODE Tooltypes "GSM's ToolTypes"

@{u}GSM's ToolTypes@{uu}

GSM can be configured using the Tool Types in its Workbench icon file.
Use the Workbench "Information" menu item to change them, or select the 
GSM @{" Save Settings " link Savesettings} menu item to save the current configuration.

The Workbench icon file is also read for the configuration when GSM was
started from the shell.

GSM supports the following ToolTypes:

   @{b}CHIP@{ub}
            Display @{" Chip memory usage " link Chip}.

   @{b}FAST@{ub}
            Display @{" Fast memory usage " link Fast}.

   @{b}CPU@{ub}
            Display @{" CPU idle rate " link CPU}.

If neither of the CHIP, FAST and CPU tooltypes are present, all three are 
displayed. This is because it is rather silly to start GSM if you don't 
want to see any of its displays.

   @{b}NOFRAG@{ub}
            Do not display memory @{" fragmentation " link Fragmentation}.

   @{b}NOGRID@{ub}
            Do not display a @{" grid " link Grid}.

   @{b}DELAY=@{i}number_of_milliseconds@{ui}@{ub}
            Set the @{" delay " link Delay} between display updates. The minimum delay
            is 250 ms, the maximum is 5000 ms (5 seconds).
            Default delay is 1 second.

   @{b}WINDOW=@{i}left@{ui}/@{i}top@{ui}/@{i}width@{ui}/@{i}height@{ui}@{ub}
            Set the initial @{" window dimensions " link Window}.
            Default window dimensions are 0/0/260/120.

   @{b}PUBSCREEN=@{i}Public Screen Name@{ui}@{ub}
            The name of the @{" screen " link Pubscreen} GSM should open its window on.
            Default screen is the current default public screen (usually
            the Workbench screen).

   @{b}FONT=@{i}fontname.font@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}FONTH=@{i}font height@{ui}@{ub}
            The @{" font " link Font} name and height to use for displaying text.
            Default is the system's default font.

   @{b}BGPEN=@{i}pen number@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}FG1PEN=@{i}pen number@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}FG2PEN=@{i}pen number@{ui}@{ub}
   @{b}GRIDPEN=@{i}pen number@{ui}@{ub}
            The @{" pen numbers " link Colors} to use for drawing the graphs.
            Default are the screen's background, text, highlight and fill
            pens, respectively.

   @{b}TITLEBAR=@{i}yes_or_no@{ui}@{ub}
            Open the window with or without @{" title bar " link Titlebar}.
            Default is to open with title bar.

GSM's tooltypes are not case-sensitive.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Features "GSM Features"

@{u}GSM Features@{uu}

System information:
   o  Amount of free @{" chip memory " link Chip} and optional @{" fragmentation " link Fragmentation} rate
   o  Amount of free @{" fast memory " link Fast} and optional @{" fragmentation " link Fragmentation} rate
   o  @{" CPU " link CPU} idle rate
 * o  @{" Difference " link Remember} in free memory since some settable starting point

Other features:
   o  User control of the @{" speed " link Delay} at which the graphs proceed
   o  Optional @{" grid " link Grid} in the graph displays
   o  Fully resizeable @{" window " link Window}
   o  Memory @{" flush " link Flush} option
   o  Non-modal @{" About " link About} requester
 * o  User settable @{" colors " link Colors} for the graphs
 * o  User settable @{" font " link Font} to use for text
 * o  Window opens on any @{" public screen " link Pubscreen}
 * o  Window opens with or without @{" title bar " link Titlebar}
 * o  Settings can be @{" saved " link Savesettings} in the Workbench icon file

* These features are new for version 1.3

--------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Quick Start:
   There are no more Quick Start links.
   Click on any of the above to see more about that feature of GSM,
   or go back to @{" Installation " link Installation}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Menus "GSM Menus"

@{u}GSM Menus@{uu}

The GSM Menus are layed out in the following way:


  @{u} Project     @{uu}
   @{" Flush            " link Flush}
   @{" Flush & Remember " link Remember}
   @{" ---------------- " link Menus}
   @{" Save Settings    " link Savesettings}
   @{" ---------------- " link Menus}
   @{" About...         " link About}
   @{" Quit             " link Quit}


  @{u} Display          @{uu}
   @{" Chip Memory   " link Chip}
   @{" Fast Memory   " link Fast}
   @{" Fragmentation " link Fragmentation}
   @{" CPU Idle      " link CPU}
   @{" ------------- " link Menus}
   @{" Grid          " link Grid}
   @{" ------------- " link Menus}
   @{" Title Bar     " link Titlebar}

Click on an item to see more.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Flush "Flush Memory"

@{u}Flush Memory@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Flush memory from within GSM.
   All disk-based libraries, devices, fonts, etc that are no longer in use
   are removed from memory.

MENU SELECTION
   Project / Flush

KEYBOARD SELECTION
   Right-Amiga F

@ENDNODE
@NODE Remember "Flush Memory and Remember"

@{u}Flush Memory and Remember@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Memory is flushed like the @{" flush " link Flush} function.
   The resulting amount of free memory is remembered, and the difference
   between the remembered and actual amounts of free memory is displayed
   in the @{" Chip " link Chip} and @{" Fast " link Fast} memory graphs.

   Note that Intuition may allocate memory for its IDCMP messages while
   a window is open. Just clicking in a window may result in allocation of
   some memory, as is any other Intuition event. This memory will not be
   freed by Intuition until the window is closed.

MENU SELECTION
   Project / Flush & Remember

KEYBOARD SELECTION
   Right-Amiga R

@ENDNODE
@NODE Savesettings "Save Settings"

@{u}Save Settings@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   The current configuration of GSM is written to its Workbench icon file
   as @{" Tool Type " link Tooltypes} values.

   If GSM cannot find its icon file, nothing is saved.

MENU SELECTION
   Project / Save Settings

@ENDNODE
@NODE About "About GSM"

@{u}About GSM@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Shows a requester with version number and copyright information.

   Unlike the About requesters of virtually all other programs, this is
   a @{i}non-modal@{ui} system requester. Non-modal means, it does not suspend
   the operation of the program.

   If there is already a GSM about requester hanging around on the screen,
   that window will pop up to front and is made active.

MENU SELECTION
   Project / About...

@ENDNODE
@NODE Quit "Quit GSM"

@{u}Quit GSM@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Terminates GSM.

   If an @{" about " link About} requester is still open, that window is
   closed.

MENU SELECTION
   Project / Quit

KEYBOARD SELECTION
   Right-Amiga Q

SHELL SELECTION
   GSM listens to Control-C signals and the BREAK shell command if started
   from a @{" shell " link Shellstart}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Chip "Display free Chip memory"

@{u}Display free Chip memory@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Shows a graph of free chip memory in your system. The amount of free
   chip memory is also displayed as text, as is the difference from a
   previously @{" remembered " link Remember} amount.

   Optionally the @{" fragmentation " link Fragmentation} rate of chip memory is displayed 
   in the same graph using a second color.

   Beneath the graph is a comment line reading:
      CHIP (@{i}aaaaa@{ui}K)  @{i}bbbbb@{ui}K free (+cccccc) @{fg highlight}Frag: @{i}ddd@{ui}%@{fg text}
   where:
      @{i}aaaaa@{ui} = total amount of chip memory in the system in Kbytes.
      @{i}bbbbb@{ui} = current amount if free chip memory in Kbytes
      @{i}cccccc@{ui} = difference between the current amount of free chip
         memory and the remembered amount in bytes. Positive values mean
         there is more free memory, negative values mean there is less free
         memory.
      @{i}ddd@{ui} = chip memory fragmentation rate.
   This line might appear slightly different depending on available room in
   the window and options selected.

   The @{" speed " link Delay} at which the graph proceeds is user controllable,
   as are the @{" colors " link Colors} in which it is drawn.

MENU SELECTION
   Display / Chip Memory
   This menu item toggles the chip memory display.

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the CHIP @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes} to get the chip memory display.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the CHIP @{" argument " link ShellStart} to get the chip memory display.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Fast "Display free Fast memory"

@{u}Display free Fast memory@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Shows a graph of free fast memory in your system. The amount of free
   fast memory is also displayed as text, as is the difference from a
   previously @{" remembered " link Remember} amount.

   Optionally the @{" fragmentation " link Fragmentation} rate of fast memory is displayed 
   in the same graph using a second color.

   Beneath the graph is a comment line reading:
      FAST (@{i}aaaaa@{ui}K)  @{i}bbbbb@{ui}K free (+cccccc) @{fg highlight}Frag: @{i}ddd@{ui}%@{fg text}
   where:
      @{i}aaaaa@{ui} = total amount of fast memory in the system in Kbytes.
      @{i}bbbbb@{ui} = current amount if free fast memory in Kbytes
      @{i}cccccc@{ui} = difference between the current amount of free fast
         memory and the remembered amount in bytes. Positive values mean
         there is more free memory, negative values mean there is less free
         memory.
      @{i}ddd@{ui} = fast memory fragmentation rate.
   This line might appear slightly different depending on available room in
   the window and options selected.

   The @{" speed " link Delay} at which the graph proceeds is user controllable,
   as are the @{" colors " link Colors} in which it is drawn.

MENU SELECTION
   Display / Fast Memory
   This menu item toggles the fast memory display.

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the FAST @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes} to get the fast memory display.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the FAST @{" argument " link ShellStart} to get the fast memory display.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Fragmentation "Display memory fragmentation"

@{u}Display memory fragmentation@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Shows a graph of chip and fast memory fragmentation rate.
   The graph is displayed in the free @{" chip " link Chip} and @{" fast " link Fast} memory displays,
   using a second color to make it distinguishable from the free memory
   graph.

   Fragmentation is not displayed if the corresponding memory display is
   not selected.

   Fragmentation is computed as a percentage:
     0% means that all free memory is in one (large) block
   100% means that all free memory is scattered around in many little pieces

MENU SELECTION
   Display / Fragmentation
   This menu item toggles the fragmentation graph in the free memory
   displays.

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the NOFRAG @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes} to prevent the fragmentation display.
   By default the fragmentation rate is displayd.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the NOFRAG @{" argument " link ShellStart} to prevent the fragmentation display, or the
   FRAG @{" argument " link Shellstart} to override a NOFRAG @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes}.
   By default the fragmentation rate is displayd.

SEE ALSO
   @{" How fragmentation is computed " link Frag_Compute}

@ENDNODE
@NODE CPU "Display CPU idle rate"

@{u}Display CPU idle rate@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Shows a graph of the average CPU idle rate.

   CPU idle rate is computed as a percentage of the (real) time that the
   CPU is not busy with any task, averaged over the measurement time 
   interval.
     0% means the CPU was busy all the time
   100% means the CPU was not busy at all.
   In practice, 100% will never be reached, because there are always 
   several background system tasks that consume some CPU time, including
   GSM itself.

   Beneath the graph is a comment line reading:
      CPU Idle @{i}aaa@{ui}%
   where:
      @{i}aaa@{ui} = current CPU idle rate.
   This line might appear slightly different depending on available room in
   the window.

   The @{" speed " link Delay} at which the graph proceeds is user controllable,
   as are the @{" colors " link Colors} in which it is drawn.

MENU SELECTION
   Display / CPU Idle
   This menu item toggles the CPU idle rate display.

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the CPU @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes} to get the CPU idle rate display.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the CPU @{" argument " link ShellStart} to get the CPU idle rate display.

SEE ALSO
   @{" How CPU idle time is measured " link Idle_Measure}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Grid "Show a grid in the displays"

@{u}Show a grid in the displays@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Shows a grid in the @{" free chip memory " link Chip}, @{" free fast memory " link Fast}
   and @{" CPU idle rate " link CPU} displays.

   The grid is displayed in the selected @{" grid color " link Colors}.
   The grid consists of horizontal lines at 25%, 50% and 75%, and vertical
   lines after every 15 seconds.

   After every minute, the vertical line is drawn as a solid line.

   If the @{" window height " link Window} is too small, the 25% and 75% horizontal 
   lines are not drawn.

MENU SELECTION
   Display / Grid
   This menu item toggles the grid in the displays on and off.

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the NOGRID @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes} to turn the grid off.
   By default the grid is turned on.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the NOGRID @{" argument " link ShellStart} to turn the grid off, or the GRID @{" argument " link Shellstart}
   to override a NOGRID @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes}.
   By default the grid is turned on.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Delay "Control the measurement intervals"

@{u}Control the measurement intervals@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Controls the time to elapse between successive system analyses. This
   effects the speed at which the graphs are drawn.

   The intervals can vary between 250 ms (0.25 seconds) and 5000 ms
   (5 seconds).

MOUSE SELECTION
   Use the slider in the right window border to change the interval
   delay.

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the DELAY=@{i}milliseconds@{ui} @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes} to set the initial interval delay.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the DELAY @{i}milliseconds@{ui} @{" argument " link ShellStart} to set the initial interval delay.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Window "Changing the window dimensions"

@{u}Changing the window dimensions@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   The GSM window is fully resizeable. If resized, the displays are resized
   too, to reflect the new window size.

MOUSE SELECTION
   Use the standard window drag bar, sizing gadget and zoom gadget to
   move or resize the window.

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the WINDOW=@{i}left@{ui}/@{i}top@{ui}/@{i}width@{ui}/@{i}height@{ui}@{ub} @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes} to set the initial
   window dimensions.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the WINDOW @{i}left@{ui}/@{i}top@{ui}/@{i}width@{ui}/@{i}height@{ui}@{ub} @{" argument " link ShellStart} to set the initial
   window dimensions.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Pubscreen "Public Screen selection"

@{u}Public Screen selection@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Allows the GSM window to open on any public screen.
   If the selected screen cannot be found, the default public screen
   (usually the Workbench) is used. 

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the PUBSCREEN=@{i}Public Screen Name@{ui} @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes} to select the screen.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the PUBSCREEN @{i}Public_Screen_Name@{ui} @{" argument " link Shellstart} to select the screen.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Font "Font Selection"

@{u}Font Selection@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Select the font to be used for text displays. Both fixed and
   proportional fonts may be used.
   If the font cannot be opened, the system's default font is used.

   I haven't included an ASL font requester in the program. Why not?
   Because the ASL requesters are modal requesters, they stop the program
   if they are opened. And a program like GSM should continue to operate,
   even if requesters are open.

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the FONT=@{i}fontname.font@{ui} and FONTH=@{i}font height@{ui} @{" tooltypes " link Tooltypes} to set the
   font to be used. The font name should include the ".font" extension.
   Both a FONT and a FONTH must be present to use the font.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the FONT=@{i}fontname.font@{ui} and FONTH=@{i}font height@{ui} @{" arguments " link Shellstart} to set the
   font to be used. See the notes in the previous paragraph.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Colors "Graph colors"

@{u}Graph colors@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   Pick the pen numbers to use when drawing graphs.

   Four colors are recognized:
      BGPEN = background of graph.
      FG1PEN = foreground 1, used for the first function line in a graph.
      FG2PEN = foreground 2, used for the second function line in a graph.
      GRIDPEN = grid color.

   Sharable pens can be used, but they will not be properly obtained by
   GSM.

KEYBOARD SELECTION
   Use function keys F1 to F4 to cycle through the available pens. Combine
   with the SHIFT key to cycle backwards.
      F1 = cycle BGPEN
      F2 = cycle FG1PEN
      F3 = cycle FG2PEN
      F4 = cycle GRIDPEN

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the BGPEN=@{i}pen number@{ui}, FG1PEN=@{i}pen number@{ui}, FG2PEN=@{i}pen number@{ui} and
   GRIDPEN=@{i}pen number@{ui} @{" tooltypes " link Tooltypes} to set the colors.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the BGPEN @{i}pen_number@{ui}, FG1PEN @{i}pen_number@{ui}, FG2PEN @{i}pen_number@{ui} and
   GRIDPEN @{i}pen_number@{ui} @{" arguments " link Shellstart} to set the colors.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Titlebar "Window without title bar"

@{u}Window without title bar@{uu}

DESCRIPTION
   By default, GSM opens a normal window with title bar.
   As an option, the window can be without title bar, and close, zoom and
   depth gadgets.

MENU SELECTION
   Display / Title Bar
   This menu item toggles the title bar.

WORKBENCH TOOLTYPE
   Use the TITLEBAR=@{i}yes_or_no@{ui} @{" tooltype " link Tooltypes} to control the title bar.
   Valid tool type values are:
      @{b}NO@{ub} or @{b}0@{ub}: open window without title bar
      any other value: open window with title bar.

SHELL ARGUMENT
   Use the TITLEBAR @{i}yes_or_no@{ui} @{" argument " link Shellstart} to control the title bar.
   See the previous paragraph for valid values.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Frag_Compute "How memory fragmentation is computed"

@{u}How memory fragmentation is computed@{uu}

@{i}What is memory fragmentation?@{ui}
If free memory is not available as one large chunk, but merely as many
smaller chunks, memory is fragmented.
Memory fragmentation can occur when programs have allocated many separate
pieces of memory, and have not yet returned all these pieces to the
system.
When memory is returned, the Exec will mend adjacent pieces of free memory
together into a larger block, thus decreasing memory fragmentation.

If memory is fragmented, a memory allocation of a large block could fail,
although the total amount of free memory could be sufficient. Allocation
fails because the free memory is subdivided into several parts, each not
sufficiently large to honour the allocation request.
For example: if there are 2 chunks of 512 kB free memory (total 1MB),
and a program requests 513 kB, the allocation will fail.

It is obvious that memory fragmentation is a bad thing.

@{i}How is the percentage that GSM shows, computed?@{ui}
The most important factor is the ratio

    size of largest chunk
   @{b}------------------------@{ub}                     [1]
    total free memory size

Fragmentation increases if this ratio is smaller. To scale it into [0,1],
the factor

          size of largest chunk
   ( 1 - @{b}------------------------@{ub} )             [2]
          total free memory size

is computed. This factor will be zero if all free memory is in one large
chunk, and approaches 1 if free memory is scattered into many small chunks.

The second important factor is the number of free memory chunks. This
is intuitively a measure of fragmentation.
Moreover, if there are more free memory chunks, there is a bigger chance
that any freed memory will mend up with a chunk that is not the largest
chunk, thereby decreasing factor [1].
This leads to a second factor, scaled into [0,1]:

                    1
   ( 1 - @{b}-----------------------@{ub} )              [3]
          number of free chunks

The fragmentation percentage as displayed by GSM is the product of
[2] and [3].

This way of expressing memory fragmentation as a percentage is undoubtedly
arbitrary, as is every other way.
If you think you have a better way of computing this percentage, please
send @{" me " link Author} an E-mail.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Idle_Measure "How CPU idle time is measured"

@{u}How CPU idle time is measured@{uu}

When the CPU is idle, there is currently no task to be executed. So how can
you measure this time if nothing is running?

GSM takes advantage of a property of the operating system, namely, that a
task with lower priority will @{i}never@{ui} be executed as long as there are
tasks with higher priority ready to run.
To measure the CPU idle time, GSM starts a dummy task at the lowest
possible priority, -128. This task will get the CPU @{i}only@{ui} if nothing else
wants to be run.
Using special Switch and Launch routines, this dummy tasks reads the system
clock every time it is launched (execution starts) and switched (execution
is suspended).

The total time for which this dummy task has run in a specific interval,
is the elapsed time for which no other task was ready to run, i.e. the
CPU idle time.

GSM uses E-clock values for maximum accuracy. In fact, the idle time
measurement is so accurate you can notice the CPU usage when you move the
mouse, for instance.

It is obvious that GSM's strategy doesn't work if there are other tasks in
the system running at -128 priority. In particular, if you run GSM more
than once at the same time, the CPU idle rate displayed is not accurate.
Also, some screen savers (like the standard Workbench screensaver) operate
on this priority.

